record_data.record_plain_text:
TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT BETWEEN RAINBOW ENERGY CENTER, LLC, AND NEXUS LINE, LLC This Transmission Service Agreement (this "Agreement") is made and entered into this July 21, 2021, by and between Nexus Line, LLC ("Nexus") and Rainbow Energy Center, LLC ("REC"). Nexus and REC may each be referred to individually herein as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties." RECITALS A. Whereas REC, is the owner of the Coal Creek Generating Station, a 1,151 MW coal-fired generation facility located in Underwood, North Dakota; and B. Whereas REC sells power from the Coal Creek Generating Station to Great River Energy at the Point of Interconnection at Dickinson Substation in Buffalo, Minnesota; and C. Whereas Nexus owns certain Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities to the Point of Interconnection; and D. Whereas Great River Energy owns Transmission Owner Interconnection Facilities to the Point of Interconnection; and E. Whereas FERC Open Access and Priority Rights on Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, Order No. 807, 80 Fed. Reg. 17,653 (Apr. 1, 2015), FERC Stats. & Regs. 31,367 at P 36, order on reh'g and compliance, 153 FERC 61,047 (2015), recognizes that Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities "often involve[s] unique circumstances that would benefit from negotiations to tailor individual access agreements" and F. Whereas REC desires to enter into an individual access agreement with Nexus over the Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities to make sales at the Dickinson Substation in Buffalo, Minnesota to Great River Energy. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing premises and the mutual undertakings set forth below, the Parties, intending to be legally bound, hereby agree as follows: 1. DEFINITIONS The following terms when used herein with initial capitalization, whether in the singular or the plural, shall have the following meanings: 1.1 "Coal Creek Generating Station" has the meaning given to such term in the Recitals. 1.2 "Affiliate" means, with respect to any Person, any other Person that, directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, or is controlled by, or is under common control with, such first Person. For purposes of this definition, the term "control" means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management and policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities, by contract or otherwise. 1.3 "Agreement" means this Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service Agreement. 1.4 "Base Term" has the meaning given to such term in Section 2.2. 1.5 "Breach" has the meaning given to such term in Section 7.1. 1.6 "Breaching Party" has the meaning given to such term in Section 7.2. 1.7 "Coal Creek Substation" means the 230-kV substation and associated facilities located in Underwood, North Dakota. 1.8 "Converter Stations" means (i) the Converter and all assets included within it, including the high voltage direct current ("HVDC") equipment located in buildings or outdoors, located south of Underwood, North Dakota, in an industrial area adjacent to the Coal Creek Generating Station, located at latitude: 47o22'25"N, longitude: 101o09'25"W; and (ii) the Converter and all assets included within it, including the HVDC equipment (but excluding any AC equipment) located in buildings or outdoors, located south-east of Buffalo, Minnesota, located at latitude: 45o06'39"N, longitude: 93o48'36"W, 1.9 "Curtailment" means a reduction in Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service in response to a transmission capacity shortage on the Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities, or any part thereof, as a result of system reliability conditions or an unplanned outage. 1.10 "Default" has the meaning given to such term in Section 7.1. 1.11 "Delivery Point" means the Dickinson Substation. 1.12 "Dickinson Substation" means the substation located in Buffalo, Minnesota where power from Coal Creek Generating Station is injected into the Midcontinent Independent System Operator grid. 1.13 "FERC" has the meaning given to such term in Section 2.1. 1.14 "Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service" means the services provided by Nexus to transmit power generated by Plant from the Point of Receipt to the Delivery Point via the Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities pursuant to the terms of this Agreement. 1.15 "Force Majeure" means any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any Curtailment, any order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental, military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a Party's control. A Force Majeure event does not include acts of negligence or intentional wrongdoing by the Party claiming Force Majeure. 1.16 "Good Utility Practice" means any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in, or approved by, a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the term, or, if there are no such practices, methods, and acts with respect to any specific conditions or circumstances, any of the practices, methods, and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety, and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act, to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be a spectrum of acceptable practices, methods, or acts. 1.17 "HVDC Line" means the approximately 436-mile HVDC transmission line between the Converter Stations. 1.18 "ICIF" means Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities 1.19 "Indemnified Party" has the meaning given to such term in Section 10.1. 1.20 "Indemnifying Party" has the meaning given to such term in Section 10.1. 1.21 "Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facility" means the Coal Creek Substation, the Converter Stations and the HVDC Line. 1.22 "Monthly Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service Charge" means the monthly charge for Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service as set forth in Appendix A. 1.23 "Nexus" means Nexus Line, LLC, a North Dakota limited liability company. 1.24 "Non-Breaching Party" has the meaning given to such term in Section 7.2. 1.25 "Person" means any individual, corporation, partnership, limited liability company, trust, association or other entity or organization, including any governmental or political subdivision or any agency or instrumentality thereof. 1.26 "Plant" means the Coal Creek Generating Station. 1.27 "Point of Receipt" or "POR" means the Coal Creek Substation. 1.28 "Prime Rate" means, for any period, the "Prime Rate" per annum, determined as of the date the obligation to pay interest arises, and adjusted from time to time thereafter, as reported by the Wall Street Journal as the base rate on corporate loans posted by at least seventy-five percent (75%) of the nation's thirty (30) largest banks for such day as such "Prime Rate" may change from time to time. In the event the Wall Street Journal ceases to publish the "Prime Rate," then the Parties shall agree as to a substitute reference that represents the base rate on corporate loans posted by major banks having one or more lending offices in New York, New York. 1.29 "Renewal Term" has the meaning given to such term in Section 2.3. 1.30 "REC" means Rainbow Energy Center, LLC, a North Dakota limited liability company. 2. EFFECTIVE DATE AND TERM 2.1 This Agreement shall become effective on the date it is accepted for filing under section 205 of the Federal Power Act by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC"). 2.2 This Agreement shall continue in effect for one year from the date of effectiveness of this Agreement as determined by FERC pursuant to Section 2.1 ("Base Term"), unless earlier terminated by mutual agreement of the Parties or in accordance with Section 8. 2.3 The Base Term shall automatically be extended for one or more additional one-year terms (each, a "Renewal Term") unless either party provides written notice to the other not less than sixty (60) days prior to the end of the Base Term or any Renewal Term, as the case may be, of its intention to terminate this Agreement. 3. SERVICES 3.1 Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service 3.1.1 Nexus shall provide 1125 MW of Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service for the Plant from the Point of Receipt to the Delivery Point. At any time during a Renewal Term, REC shall have the right to reduce the amount of Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service set forth in this Section 3.1.1. 3.1.2 Nexus shall not be responsible for transmission line losses (using a dynamic loss calculation) on the Interconnection Customer Interconnection Facilities. Such line losses shall be REC's responsibility. 3.1.3 Nexus shall only undertake Curtailment on the ICIF, or any portion thereof, as required to maintain reliable operation of the ICIF consistent with Good Utility Practice. Nexus will provide advance notice of Curtailment where such notice can be provided consistent with Good Utility Practice.
3.2 Operations 3.2.1 Nexus shall own, operate, and maintain the ICIF in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 3.2.2 Nexus shall exercise reasonable efforts to coordinate scheduling of maintenance and other planned outages of the ICIF with REC, subject to Good Utility Practices and Nexus's operating procedures, with a goal of avoiding scheduling any such activities at times which would interfere with REC's scheduled energy deliveries. Nexus shall notify REC of all outages of the ICIF. Nexus, however, shall retain sole and full operational control of the ICIF. 4. CHARGES 4.1 During the Base Term and Renewal Term of this Agreement, REC shall pay to Nexus each month the Monthly Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service Charge, as set forth in Appendix A. If this Agreement is terminated under the terms of Section 8, REC shall pay to Nexus the amounts specified in such section. 4.2 In addition to the payments set forth described in Section 4.1, REC shall pay to Nexus any sales or use taxes payable by Nexus from time to time with respect to the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service under this Agreement, provided that REC shall be entitled to participate in any proceeding before any applicable taxing authority or court as to whether any such taxes are payable by Nexus. 4.3 Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, each Party agrees to pay any and all local, state and federal taxes, including income, franchise, property, excise, or any other taxes which are now, or in the future may be, assessed and legally owed by such Party pertaining to the services performed under this Agreement. 5. BILLING AND PAYMENT 5.1 Nexus shall render bills individually to REC for charges described in Section 4 not later than the twenty fifth (25th) day of the month immediately following the month in which the related Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service was provided. 5.2 Subject to Section 5.4, REC shall pay Nexus's bill within thirty (30) days of receipt. 5.3 Payments as required by Section 5.1 that are not made in full by REC by the due date specified in Section 5.2 shall thereafter accrue interest at an annual rate equal to the then-current Prime Rate plus two percent. Interest shall accrue on the unpaid balance prorated by days until payment in full is made. At any time, if the then-current Prime Rate plus two percent is deemed to be unlawful, then the maximum legal interest rate which is applicable to this Agreement shall apply. 5.4 In the event REC desires to dispute all or any part of any bill submitted by Nexus, REC shall nevertheless pay the undisputed amount of the bill when due and shall give notification in writing within thirty (30) days from the date of the billing stating the grounds for the dispute and the amount in dispute. If an adjustment in favor of REC is made in the billing, Nexus shall pay interest at an annual rate equal to the then-current Prime Rate plus two percent. Interest shall accrue on the amount of the adjustment prorated to the date of payment. 5.5 All payments to be made by REC to Nexus shall be sent to: Nexus Line, LLC 919 South Seventh St. Suite 405 Bismarck, ND 58504
Nexus may, at any time by written notice to REC, change the address to which payments shall be sent. 5.6 All bills and payments, if any, by Nexus to REC shall be sent to: Rainbow Energy Center, LLC 919 South Seventh St. Suite 405 Bismarck, ND 58504
REC may, at any time by written notice to Nexus, change the address to which bills and/or payments, if any, shall be sent. 6. FORCE MAJEURE 6.1 Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, neither Party shall be considered to be in Default or Breach of this Agreement or liable in damages or otherwise responsible to the other Party for any delay in or failure to carry out any of its obligations under this Agreement if, and only to the extent that, it is unable to perform or is prevented from performing by an event of Force Majeure. A Force Majeure exemption from liability will extend for the period of time necessitated by such event of Force Majeure. Such event of Force Majeure will not relieve either Party of its obligation to make payments hereunder. 6.2 In the event of Force Majeure, a Party's obligations can only be excused to the extent and for the period that the Party's inability to perform is caused by an event of Force Majeure affecting the Party and only to the extent of the duration of the same, provided that the Party claiming Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to cure, mitigate or remedy the effects of the Force Majeure event. Nothing herein shall be construed to require either Party to settle a labor dispute, lockout or strike. 6.3 A Party claiming Force Majeure as a basis for being excused from performance of its obligations under this Agreement must: (i) provide oral notice that is prompt under the circumstances, followed by written notice of the occurrence of the Force Majeure event to the other Party no later than ten (10) business days after the occurrence of the event which provides an estimate of the event's expected duration and the probable impact on the performance of the Party's obligations hereunder; (ii) exercise all reasonable efforts in accordance with Good Utility Practice to continue to perform its obligations under this Agreement; (iii) expeditiously take reasonable action to correct or cure the Force Majeure event, provided, however, that settlement of strikes or other labor disputes is completely within the sole discretion of the Party affected by such strike or labor dispute; and (iv) provide prompt notice to the other Party of the cessation of the Force Majeure event. Failure to provide notice of the occurrence of the Force Majeure event required hereunder shall preclude such Party from relying upon Force Majeure to excuse its failure to perform or avoid breach or default as a result of such failure. 7. BREACH, CURE AND DEFAULT 7.1 A breach of this Agreement shall occur upon the failure by a Party to pay any amount when due or to perform or observe any other material term or condition of this Agreement ("Breach"). A default of this Agreement shall occur upon the failure of a Party in Breach of this Agreement to cure such Breach ("Default"). 7.2 Upon the occurrence of an event of Breach, the Party not in Breach (the "Non- Breaching Party"), when it becomes aware of the Breach, shall give written notice of the Breach to the Party in Breach (the "Breaching Party"). Such notice shall set forth, in reasonable detail, the nature of the Breach, and where known and applicable, the steps necessary to cure such Breach. Upon receiving written notice of the Breach hereunder, the Breaching Party shall have thirty (30) days to cure such Breach. If the Breach is such that it cannot be cured within thirty (30) days, the Breaching Party will commence in good faith all steps as are reasonable and appropriate to cure the Breach within such thirty (30) daytime period and thereafter diligently pursue such action to completion. In the event the Breaching Party fails to cure the Breach within ninety (90) days of becoming aware of the Breach, the Breaching Party will be in Default of this Agreement. If the Non-Breaching Party (or any lender thereof) chooses to cure a Breaching Party's default, the Breaching Party shall reimburse the Non-Breaching Party (or such Party's lender) upon demand for all commercially reasonable costs incurred by the non-breaching Party (or such Non-Breaching Party's lender) in curing such breach. 8. TERMINATION 8.1 A Party may terminate this Agreement upon the Default of the other Party. Subject to the limitations set forth in Section 7, in the event of a Default, the non-Defaulting Party may terminate this Agreement only upon the later of: 8.1.1 its giving of written notice of termination to the other Party, to any lender of such Party if permitted under Section 13 and of which the other Party has written notice; and 8.1.2 the acceptance by FERC of a notice of termination of this Agreement (if required by law). Termination of this Agreement shall not relieve either Party of any of its liabilities and obligations arising hereunder prior to the date termination becomes effective, and each Party may take whatever judicial or administrative actions as appear necessary or desirable to enforce its rights hereunder. 9. WAIVERS 9.1 Any waiver at any time by either Party of its rights with respect to a Breach or Default under this Agreement, or with respect to any other matter arising from this Agreement, shall not be deemed a waiver with respect to any subsequent Breach or Default or other matter arising in connection therewith. Any delay, with the exception of the statutory period of limitation in assessing or enforcing any right, shall not be deemed a waiver of such right. 10. INDEMNIFICATION 10.1 Each Party (the "Indemnifying Party") agrees to indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other party (the "Indemnified Party") from and against all claims, demands, losses, liabilities, penalties, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) for personal injury or death to persons and damage to the Indemnified Party' real property and tangible personal property or facilities or the property of any other person or entity to the extent arising out of, resulting from, or caused by a Breach under this Agreement, or by the negligent or tortious acts, errors, or omissions of the Indemnifying Party, its affiliates, its directors, officers, employees, or agents. The indemnification of third-party claims provided under this Section 10 is not limited by the limitation on damages set forth in Section 11. Nothing in this Section 10 shall enlarge or relieve a Party of any liability to the other Party for any breach of this Agreement. This indemnification obligation shall apply notwithstanding any negligent or intentional acts, errors or omissions of the Indemnified Party, but the Indemnifying Party's liability to pay damages to the Indemnified Party shall be reduced in proportion to the percentage by which the Indemnified Party's negligent or intentional acts, errors or omissions caused or contributed to the damages. Neither Party shall be indemnified for its damages resulting from its sole negligence, intentional acts or willful misconduct. These indemnity provisions shall not be construed to relieve any insurer of its obligation to pay claims consistent with the provisions of a valid insurance policy. 11. LIMITATION OF LIABILITY NO PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR CONSEQUENTIAL, INCIDENTAL, PUNITIVE, EXEMPLARY OR INDIRECT DAMAGES, LOST PROFITS OR OTHER BUSINESS INTERRUPTION DAMAGES BY STATUTE, IN TORT OR CONTRACT (EXCEPT TO THE EXTENT EXPRESSLY PROVIDED HEREIN); PROVIDED, THAT IF EITHER PARTY IS HELD LIABLE TO A THIRD PARTY FOR SUCH DAMAGES AND THE PARTY HELD LIABLE FOR SUCH DAMAGES IS ENTITLED TO INDEMNIFICATION THEREFOR FROM THE OTHER PARTY HERETO, THE INDEMNIFYING PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE FOR AND OBLIGATED TO REIMBURSE THE INDEMNIFIED PARTY FOR, SUCH DAMAGES. 12. GOVERNING LAW 12.1 This Agreement shall be interpreted by and in accordance with the laws of the State of North Dakota or the laws of the United States, as applicable, as if executed and to be performed wholly within the State of North Dakota. 13. ASSIGNMENT 13.1 A Party may sell, assign or otherwise transfer, voluntarily or by operation of law, all or any part of its rights under this Agreement with the written consent of the other Party, such consent to not be unreasonably withheld. The assignment or transfer of direct or indirect equity interests in a Party which results in a change in control (as such term is defined in the definition of "Affiliate") of such Party shall be deemed an assignment of such Party's rights under this Agreement for purposes of this Article 13. 14. FURTHER ASSURANCES 14.1 Each Party acknowledges that the other Party may finance its interest in the Plant or ICIF, as applicable, with funds to be provided, in whole or in part, by lenders, some or all of which are yet to be identified. Each Party agrees to execute, acknowledge and deliver any and all further documents and instruments to the other Party, and to take any other actions, which may be necessary or desirable to (i) accommodate such Party's financing or any refinancing thereof, (ii) satisfy the requests of any lender or prospective lender in connection with such financing or refinancing, (iii) obtain any authorization necessary or convenient in connection with the funding of such Party's interest in the Plant or ICIF, as applicable, or the, ownership, operation or maintenance of the Plant or ICIF, as applicable, or (iv) otherwise effectuate the purpose and intent of this Agreement. 14.2 Each Party agrees to provide such information and documentation as may be requested by the other Party's lender or prospective lender, including (i) financial statements, evidence of corporate existence, and evidence of incumbency of persons executing this Agreement; (ii) an opinion of its counsel confirming the enforceability of this Agreement against such Party and the accuracy of the representations set forth herein, and addressing such other matters as may be requested by any such lender or prospective lender, (iii) a consent to the collateral assignment of this Agreement to any such lender containing such terms as are commonly required by lenders, including a right to cure any Default by such Party, and (iv) any other consents, estoppel certificates or other documents required in connection with the financing or refinancing of the Plant or ICIF, as applicable.
14.3 In the event that any Party intending to obtain financing or any lender or prospective lender to such Party determines that any amendment or modification to this Agreement is required in connection with or as a condition to the financing or refinancing of the Plant or the ICIF, as applicable, the Parties shall immediately negotiate in good faith, and in consultation with any such lender or prospective lender, the terms of, and shall execute, any and all such amendments or modifications as are mutually agreed by the Parties. 16. NOTICES Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, any notice, demand, or request provided for in this Agreement, or served, given, or made in connection with this Agreement, shall be in writing and shall be deemed properly served, given, or made if delivered in person, by overnight express delivery service, or by electronic delivery to the person specified below: For Rainbow Energy Center, LLC Stacy L. Tschider Rainbow Energy Center, LLC 919 South Seventh Street, Suite 405 Bismarck, ND 58504 Tel. (701) 222-2290 E-mail: s.tschider@rainbowenergy.com
For Nexus Line, LLC Jeffrey Jonson Nexus Line, LLC 919 South Seventh Street, Suite 405 Bismarck, ND 58504 Tel. (701) 222-2290 E-mail: j.jonson@rainbowenergy.com
Either Party may, at any time by notice to the other Party, change the designation or address of the person so specified as the one to receive notices pursuant to this Agreement. 17. ENTIRE AGREEMENT This Agreement constitutes the complete and final expression of the agreement between the Parties and is intended as a complete and exclusive statement of the terms of their agreement which supersedes all prior and contemporaneous offers, promises, representations, negotiations, discussions, communications, and other agreements which may have been made in connection with the subject matter of this Agreement. 18. RELATIONSHIP OF PARTIES The covenants, obligations, and liabilities of the Parties are intended to be several and not joint or collective, and nothing contained in this Agreement shall ever be construed to create an association, joint venture, trust or partnership, or to impose a trust or partnership covenant, obligation, or liability on or with regard to either Party. Each Party shall be individually responsible for its own covenants, obligations, and liabilities as provided in this Agreement. Neither Party shall be the agent of or have a right or power to bind the other Party without such other Party's express written consent. 19. NO THIRD PARTY RIGHTS The Parties do not intend to create rights in, or to grant remedies to, any third party as a beneficiary either of this Agreement or of any duty, covenant, obligation, or undertaking established herein. 20. REGULATORY AUTHORITY 20.1 Nexus shall file this Agreement with FERC as a rate schedule pursuant to section 205 of the Federal Power Act, the requirements of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, and FERC's Order No. 807, Open Access and Priority Rights on Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, 150 FERC 61,211 (2015). 20.2 The Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service Charge set forth on Appendix A shall remain in effect for the term of this Agreement as set forth in Section 2.2, and shall not be subject to change through application by either Party to the FERC pursuant to the provisions of section 205 or section 206 of the Federal Power Act absent agreement of both Parties. The Parties further agree that the standard of review that the FERC shall apply when acting on any unilaterally proposed modifications to this Agreement, either on the FERC's own motion or on behalf of a Party or any non-signatory, shall be the "public interest" standard of review rather than the "just and reasonable" standard of review.
IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this Agreement to be executed as of the date first set forth above by their duly authorized representatives as follows: RAINBOW ENERGY CENTER, LLC
By /s/ Stacy L. Tschider Name: Stacy L. Tschider Title: President
NEXUS LINE, LLC
By /s/ Jeffrey D. Jonson Name: Jeffrey D. Jonson Title: Exec. V.P.
Appendix A Monthly Firm Point-To-Point Transmission Service Charge For the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service, Nexus shall charge REC a Monthly Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service Charge of $4,464.00/MW-month increased by 2.5% each year on the 1st day of any Renewal Term as defined in Section 2.3.
